WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.500
 [music]

00:00:02.500 --> 00:00:13.000
 [music]

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
 Hello!

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:22.000
 [applause]

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
 This week coming to you live from the States of America!

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
 [applause]

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:31.000
 My name is Jay Shriver.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:36.000
 I am sitting here with Anna Chasinski, Andrew Hunter Murray and James Harkin.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.000
 And once again we have gathered around the microphones with our four favorite facts from the last seven days.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:44.000
 And in no particular order, here we go.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:46.000
 Starting with you, Chasinski.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:55.000
 My fact this week is that there was a Disneyland in England 569 years before there was one in America.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:57.000
 [laughter]

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.000
 Yeah.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
 It must have been very bad at four actually.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:04.000
 [laughter]

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:06.000
 It's just a slide and a swing.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.000
 It's just a field overrun with mice. Is that what you're saying?

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:10.000
 [laughter]

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
 Well, it was a field, so you're half right.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:22.000
 This is from a book, a new book called A New Dictionary of English Field Names, which is set to be...

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
 That sounds like a hell of a read.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:26.000
 [laughter]

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.000
 Welcome to Anna Chasinski's book club.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
 [laughter]

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:32.000
 Membership one.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.000
 No, it sounds great. And The Telegraph actually did a review of it, this obscure book.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:46.000
 And basically it's this guy who's gone back and traced 45,000 field names from various things like old tithe records and things like that.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.000
 He's called Paul Cavill and he's warning that...

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
 And he's single ladies.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:58.000
 [laughter]

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.000
 He's out there playing the field.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:07.000
 [laughter and applause]

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:10.000
 I'm not having this because I'm a huge fan of Paul's.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:16.000
 He's warned that these field names could be dying out. No one seems to be naming their fields anymore. Can you believe it?

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
 Oh no! Call the Avengers.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:22.000
 [laughter]

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:27.000
 And yet they used to. So it's a really important thing. I'm actually surprised farmers don't still name their fields.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:32.000
 Because the reason you do it is if you've got to say like, oh, if you're like, you know, where's the collie?

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:39.000
 Oh, I left him in, you know, that field that's like three along, five up. It's much easier to say, oh, I left him in Disneyland.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:47.000
 And so this one was called Disneyland because this was in 1386 he found the record, as in the record was in 1386.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.000
 He hasn't been writing the book for that long.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:56.000
 And it was the Disney family. And they were called that because they were originally from a place called Disney in France.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:01.000
 And so that was why it was called that. I guess they had one field. But yeah, they all used to be named.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:08.000
 There are still quite a lot of fields which do have names. So there is a UK field named Database with over 200,000 fields.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.000
 And do you know what the most popular name is?

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:12.000
 What?

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.000
 Big Field.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:25.000
 Yeah, I saw people online. So on Twitter, they were sort of asked, does anyone know of field names that might not be logged or just is there one near you?

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:32.000
 And a lot of people responded. My favorite one was from a guy called Tim who said, we have a first Humpty and a second Humpty.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:37.000
 So named as they're both Humpty and one is in front of the other.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:42.000
 There was Sodom Field and Gomorrah Close. Those are field names.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:50.000
 That's quite creative. So they did seem to be quite creative sometimes. They had, well, they had ketchup piece in Northamptonshire.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:55.000
 And that actually was a mushroom field because ketchup, the original ketchup was made of mushrooms.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:00.000
 So the first ever ketchup was made in 1727 out of mushrooms. That's ketchup, please.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:05.000
 There was apparently there was a field called Please Your Honor. And this was in Essex.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:11.000
 And it's thought apparently to be the place where the Lord of the Manor arranged to meet local girls.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:16.000
 And you don't want to think too much about the connection there.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
 And actually for the locals, it was useful to know these names, right?

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:27.000
 Because if you had a field with the word die-core sitch in it, that meant that you knew that there was water in it.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:35.000
 So you knew it was wet and boggy. And if it was called Yes Your Honor or whatever, you need to leave it alone on Friday nights.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.000
 But it meant that you knew something about these fields before you went there.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:49.000
 Yeah, yeah. Like if they were a weird shape. There was, you got things like footed stocking and ladies' gown tail if they were shaped like what those things.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:53.000
 Okay. Could you get in trouble if you sold your field with a misleading name?

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:59.000
 If I had a tiny field and I called it Big Field, could I be sold for a mis-selling?

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:05.000
 No, because I think only the biggest idiot purchaser is going to buy a field off you without coming and checking it out.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:11.000
 Not even asking for the measurements. No, it's called Big Field. I'm not telling you anymore.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
 What was the book called, then?

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
 The book is called A New Dictionary of English Field Names.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:22.000
 So that's the new one, because there is a book called English Field Names, A Dictionary, which is a previous book of English field names.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.000
 And that is by a man called John Field.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
 No way.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:39.000
 And it's not just a list of names in his own family.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.000
 That is amazing.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
 We need to move on to our next fact very shortly.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
 Oh my goodness. Then we should do some Disneyland stuff, I guess.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:47.000
 Sure.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:57.000
 Or some Disney stuff. So between 1993 and 2010, Miramax was owned by Disney, which means technically these are Disney films.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:06.000
 Pulp Fiction, Bridget Jones' Diary, Scream, Gangs of New York and Mansfield Park.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:12.000
 Disneyland actually has a special kind of invisible green.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:17.000
 I don't think you can be invisible and green, can you? Or can you?

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:27.000
 No, not really. But it was designed to conceal the less glam bits, because obviously the park needs to have unsexy stuff like bins and fences and things.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:30.000
 And it's not part of the cool Disney fantasy, is it?

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:36.000
 So the designers came up with a particular kind of green, which you don't really notice.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.000
 And they call it no-see-um green, because you can't really see it.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:46.000
 Although I don't know what happens if you're looking for a bin in Disneyland. It must be quite irritating.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:52.000
 So there's a thing about fields, which is that they have all... not all.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:58.000
 There's a thing about fields, which is that a lot of them have changed shape in the last 40 years.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.000
 Really? So they've gone from ladies gown to undone stocking or...?

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:06.000
 Exactly, yeah. Well, they've gone from rectangular to circular.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:07.000
 Really?

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:12.000
 If you look at the farms in America from above, they are circular. All the fields are circular.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
 Crop circles?

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
 No. No, no, no.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:18.000
 It's the aliens.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:19.000
 It's not the aliens.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:20.000
 They're here.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
 No, we know what it is.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:27.000
 It's circular fields because it's better for irrigation, so it's a more effective way.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:29.000
 You can have a well almost in the middle of the field, you know, and it...

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:35.000
 Yeah, you have one of these kind of squirting fountains that goes in a circle right there, so it only hits.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:39.000
 Yeah, it's really efficient. And we know the guy who invented it, but it's creating a massive problem

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:46.000
 because it's sucking up all America's water because it's so good that it means that farmers then plant more intensively

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
 and they grow crops which require more water because they've got this more efficient system.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:56.000
 So there's a thing called the Ogallala Aquifer, which is under the Great Plains in America.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:04.000
 It's a huge underwater pond, basically, which covers 174,000 square miles.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:05.000
 Wow.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:12.000
 It's one pond for a given value of pond, and it's being emptied really rapidly,

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
 and it's going to take hundreds of thousands of years of rain to replace it, so there's a problem.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
 Oh, so they shouldn't have been so good, basically.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:19.000
 Yeah.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:21.000
 Because they are good farmers, the Americans.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:27.000
 So they're the world's number one exporter of food by value, which is kind of unsurprising.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:28.000
 They're a big country.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
 Do you guys know what number two is?

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:31.000
 Netherlands.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.000
 These guys know.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.000
 Is it Belgium?

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.000
 It's Belgium, yeah.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:38.000
 Denmark.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:39.000
 Denmark.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:40.000
 It must be Denmark.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.000
 They're number three.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
 The poor old Dutch can't grow a thing, though.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:44.000
 It's embarrassing.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
 No, it is the Netherlands.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.000
 And this is kind of unbelievable.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
 How are you so good at farming?

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:57.000
 So the number, by amount, the world number two exporter of food by value,

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:02.000
 and they have 270 times smaller land mass than the U.S.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:07.000
 So apparently there have just been all these incredible farming innovations over the last sort of 20 years.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:12.000
 So there are greenhouses that are up to 175 acres big, one greenhouse.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:17.000
 I think all the greenhouses in the Netherlands take up the size of Manhattan, or a bit bigger than Manhattan.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:18.000
 Wow.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:19.000
 And yeah.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:20.000
 Wow.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:25.000
 So here we were making fun of that field book, and yet everyone in the audience is like, "Give me a copy."

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.000
 It's amazing.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:32.000
 The Netherlands is so good at farming, there is now a black market in cow poo.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
 It's really more of a ground market, isn't it?

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:43.000
 It's because there's loads of -- the Netherlands as a country produces 76 billion kilos of manure every year.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:44.000
 Okay.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
 And who's buying it?

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:53.000
 Well, you're only legally allowed to produce a certain amount because it's quite a pollutive stuff if it's not treated right.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:59.000
 So either there is manure fraud where people trade it secretly, or they spread it on their land at night to avoid being spotted.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:00.000
 Wow.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:01.000
 Yeah.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:04.000
 This is obviously a good fertilizer, but you're not allowed enough -- too much of it.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:05.000
 Oh, really?

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:06.000
 That's interesting.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
 Any poo smugglers in tonight?

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
 That does sound like a euphemism for something, doesn't it?

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:16.000
 I don't know about that.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
 It actually sounds like quite a cute name for your baby or something.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:20.000
 Do you call your baby that?

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:21.000
 I feel like you could.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:22.000
 Poo smuggler?

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:23.000
 You could call your baby a poo smuggler.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.000
 That's what they're doing all the time, isn't it?

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:27.000
 They're not smuggling poo.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
 Yeah, and they're in their bottom.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:34.000
 That's why you smuggle things.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:42.000
 How often at an airport do the people go up and go, "Aha!"

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:49.000
 What's this then, sir?

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:53.000
 It is time for fact number two, and that is my fact.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:11:00.000
 My fact this week is that every year in Japan, there is an annual anti-Valentine march held

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:05.000
 by a group known as the Revolutionary Alliance of Unpopular Men.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:06.000
 Wow.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:09.000
 Are they recruiting?

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:14.000
 I don't think they'd let you in on the --

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
 So yeah, this is an annual thing that happens in Japan.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:22.000
 These men are sick of what they say is "romantic capitalism," and of course they're single,

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:27.000
 and they go on street marches to sort of say this is too much.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:34.000
 It's currently being led by a guy called Takayuki Akimoto, and he likes to have placards, and

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:35.000
 he likes to take to the streets.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:40.000
 They only do it once a year, but obviously they like to have anything that has groups

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
 of people together to be protested against, so Christmas is a big thing as well.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:50.000
 They protest an annual Christmas march, but unfortunately in 2018 they couldn't get the

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.000
 permit for the park they wanted to do it in, so they had to do it indoors in a room instead,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.000
 so no one really saw that one.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.000
 And they had to clear all the video games out of the way.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
 I mean, apparently there aren't many of them, are there?

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:05.000
 No.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:06.000
 It's a handful.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:07.000
 It's double figures.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:08.000
 Yes.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:09.000
 Yeah.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:10.000
 I hope it's double figures.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:11.000
 Yeah.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:12.000
 It's quite controversial in Japan, isn't it?

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.000
 The whole Valentine's Day thing, people have really gone off it, and it's because this

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:20.000
 is something we've briefly mentioned before, but actually the 14th of February in places

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:25.000
 like Japan, Korea, Thailand, is just a day when women are supposed to give presents to

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.000
 men, and then exactly a month later men are supposed to give presents to women.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:33.000
 But apparently it's really an obligation, and so women are getting really pissed off

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:37.000
 because they feel like on the 14th of February they have to give chocolates, for instance,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
 to all of their male colleagues.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.000
 And so women are saying, you know, I'm spending hundreds and hundreds of pounds every year

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
 on colleagues I don't know or like, just giving them chocolates.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:50.000
 And then on the 14th of March the men have to do it three or two times more, so then

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
 they have to spend even more.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
 It sounds like it's got kind of out of control.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:58.000
 Yeah, but I think, you know, it's not that bad, especially for countries that export

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
 vast amounts of flowers.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:01.000
 Yeah.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:06.000
 But there's this whole vocabulary of the chocolate.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:11.000
 So this is called giri-choco, or obligation chocolate, basically.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
 Obligation chocolate.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:18.000
 Nothing says I love you like obligation chocolate.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:24.000
 And there's also honmei, which is chocolate for your true love, and there are now tomo-choco,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:30.000
 which is friend chocolates, and the best kind, jiko-choco, which is chocolate given to yourself

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.000
 as an act of self-love.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:34.000
 Wow.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
 That's quite nice.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
 When you say self-love, you just mean...

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:43.000
 I just mean no funny business.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
 That's what it says on the card when you get your chocolates, you sense yourself.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
 All right, no funny business, man.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:53.000
 You know, in China they also have a group that is like the Alliance of Unpopular Men

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:54.000
 in Japan.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:01.000
 They have single people who try to pull pranks on Valentine Day in order to stop people having

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:02.000
 a good night.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:08.000
 So there was one case in 2004 where a group of single people in Shanghai purchased every

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.000
 single odd-numbered seat for a cinema.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:16.000
 That is strong, isn't it?

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:17.000
 That's very good.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:18.000
 That's really good.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:19.000
 Yeah.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:23.000
 So yeah, it was a movie called Love Story, Beijing Love Story.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:24.000
 Yeah.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:28.000
 In the 17th and 18th centuries, Valentine's was slightly different.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:34.000
 For some places in Europe, you would choose your Valentine by drawing lots in a village.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:38.000
 So basically, it would be Valentine's Day and everyone would write down their names and

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:42.000
 they put it in a big hat and then you pick one out and that would be your Valentine.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:47.000
 And some people said that then the courtship was obliged to last until the following Valentine's

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:48.000
 Day.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:49.000
 Whoa.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:57.000
 You don't want to get old John the Pooh smuggler, do you?

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
 Oh no.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:03.000
 Actually, this is a bit like how Romans did it.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:08.000
 So Romans basically had invented the origin of Valentine's Day, which was lupicalia, which

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:13.000
 was around that February time and that was sort of morphed into Valentine's Day by a

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:14.000
 pope a few centuries later.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:19.000
 But yeah, what they did was first of all, the men sacrificed a goat and a dog and then

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:23.000
 they got the hides of the animals they'd sacrificed and they chased after women whipping them

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.000
 and then the women wanted it.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:30.000
 They queued up to be whipped because they believed it made them fertile.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:36.000
 But after all that happened, everyone was naked and then I believe...

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
 You've buried the lead on this story.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:43.000
 I thought you'd assume it's ancient Rome.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:47.000
 And then everyone picked names from a jar just like that and the name that you picked

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:51.000
 from a jar was the person you were paired up with to do sexy stuff with for the duration

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:55.000
 of the festival and that was their Valentine's and it sounds like a hell of a lot of fun.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:16:02.000
 There's another old English technique for Valentine's Day which was your Valentine would

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
 be the first person you laid eyes on on the day.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:12.000
 Okay, so this led to some people hiding below the windows of the person they wanted to date

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:17.000
 and then as soon as they woke up just going, "Surprise!"

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.000
 And that's actually mentioned in Hamlet.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:25.000
 Is it? Yeah, Ophelia says, "Tomorrow is St. Valentine's Day. All in the morning be time

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.000
 and I am made at your window to be your Valentine."

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:33.000
 Wow. That's so cool.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.000
 Valentine cards.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:40.000
 So there was a tradition in the 19th century as well as sending nice cards of sending

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
 horrible valentines to people.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:48.000
 They were called vinegar valentines and there were specific cards for all kinds of things.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:53.000
 So there were cards where you could say the recipient was drunk or ugly or stuck up.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
 All kinds of stuff.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:59.000
 There were specific cards for grocers being rude about them saying, "You've cheated me

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.000
 on my groceries."

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:05.000
 Which doesn't feel strictly relevant to Valentine's Day but it was just a good opportunity.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:13.000
 There was one with a picture of the man in the moon saying, "This is the only man who smiles on you."

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:21.000
 And they were sent without postage paid so you had to pay to receive it.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.000
 Salt in the wound.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
 And they were more popular.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:29.000
 Apparently by the 1880s they were more popular and better selling than actual Valentine's

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:31.000
 cards that said, "Nice stuff."

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:32.000
 And they're so weird.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:36.000
 If you look them up, there's one that's a coiled snake with the head of this gentleman

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
 wearing a top hat and it just says, "Beware the snake in the grass."

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:43.000
 And there's another which has these really good rhymes quite often.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:47.000
 So there's one whose rhyme is, "You're as vulgar a cat as I'd wish to meet and what's more

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:51.000
 you're devoured by pride and conceit but I fancy before very long you'll find out that

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:54.000
 everyone thinks you're an ignorant lout."

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
 Imagine that on Valentine's Day.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:00.000
 Well at least it's something.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:06.000
 Roses are red, violets are blue, tell the police, "Old John smuggles poo."

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:10.000
 [laughter]

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:11.000
 Very creepy.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:14.000
 Okay.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:17.000
 I feel like old John is now more important to this podcast than I am.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:20.000
 [laughter]

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.000
 Here's a kind of fun thing that you can do on Valentine's Day.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:27.000
 There's a French inventor who has invented to make part of the experience of the day

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:30.000
 when you're in a couple even better.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:31.000
 It's a flatulence pill.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:35.000
 So it's designed so that you have it at the beginning of the date and if you need to go

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:39.000
 and have a fart, you don't need to leave the table as I do.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.000
 [laughter]

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:45.000
 It's usually about this time of the podcast that you do, guys.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:46.000
 [laughter]

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.000
 Guys, I'll be back when I bring my mic.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:50.000
 Stupid move.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:51.000
 [laughter]

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
 Sorry, so what effect does it have?

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.000
 It starts you from farting.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:57.000
 No, no, it scents your fart.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:01.000
 So it makes it so it comes out smelling gingery or rose-like or violet.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:03.000
 [laughter]

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:07.000
 How much more disturbed would you be by a date if their ass smelled of ginger?

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
 [laughter]

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
 We need to move on to our next fact in a second.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:16.000
 In 2015, Seattle Aquarium had a Valentine's event.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:21.000
 In fact, they have this every year where you can watch octopuses have sex.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:27.000
 But the one in 2015 they had to cancel, in fact, due to cannibalism concerns.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
 [laughter]

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:33.000
 Because they were worried that their male octopus called Kong was too big for his partner

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
 and that he was going to eat her.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
 [laughter]

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:40.000
 It's awful when that happens when one person is just a bit bigger than the other

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
 and they accidentally eat their partner.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:46.000
 [laughter]

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.000
 Shall we move on to our next fact?

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:52.000
 It is time for fact number three, and that is James.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:56.000
 Okay, my fact this week is that during World War II,

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:03.000
 the sons of the ship the HMS Queen Elizabeth were cleaned by wrapping a priest in a large cloth

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:07.000
 and pulling him through the barrels like a human pipe cleaner.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:09.000
 [laughter]

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:13.000
 [applause]

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.000
 So cool.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
 It does not sound very true, does it?

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.000
 But this is true.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:26.000
 And this was, so I read this first of all in a book which is called A Field Guide, but it's not about field.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:31.000
 It's called A Field Guide to the English Clergy by Fergus Butler Gaily.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:34.000
 And it's about a guy called Lancelot Fleming.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
 And this guy was pretty amazing.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:41.000
 He was a priest and he was a priest in the services during the war.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:43.000
 But there's loads of amazing things about him.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:50.000
 He met his first wife after a massive drinking binge where he picked up and put on a motorbike helmet

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:55.000
 and then saw her in the street and said to her, "I'm a space bishop."

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:59.000
 [laughter]

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:01.000
 And three years later she married him.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.000
 [laughter]

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:06.000
 Wait, but people weren't even going into space at this point, were they?

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:08.000
 No, he was a man ahead of his time.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.000
 Wow.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.000
 But they did know that space existed.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:16.000
 Yes, and I guess they assumed you'd need to wear a helmet there.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
 I guess so.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:21.000
 Did he volunteer himself for the cannon cleaning?

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:24.000
 Yes, he did. He was a very slight man.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.000
 So it was only for the small cannons?

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:31.000
 Yeah, so I looked at Wikipedia to see what the cannons were on the HMS Queen Elizabeth.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:38.000
 And they had 16 six-inch guns, two three-inch guns, and four five-centimeter guns.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.000
 And I don't think it was those ones.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:43.000
 He could have cleaned them a bit.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:49.000
 [laughter]

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
 Five-inch gun, no problem.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:54.000
 [laughter]

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:59.000
 And for anyone thinking of writing in, "I know that's the diameter, not the length."

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
 [laughter]

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:04.000
 I thought you were just being incredibly...

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.000
 Anyway, so...

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:11.000
 They also had some 15-inch guns, which you could just about squeeze in if you had really thin shoulders,

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:15.000
 and a 21-inch torpedo tube, so I think it might have been one of those.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.000
 Chaplains in the Army, just very quickly.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:23.000
 The modern-day chaplain in the U.S. Army is flame-resistant.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:25.000
 [laughter]

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:26.000
 Who calls that?

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.000
 Okay, what do you mean by that?

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:34.000
 So this is from Mary Roach's book, Grunt, and she points out the man of cloth has various different cloths

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:40.000
 that he can wear when he's going into, say, a tank, or if he's just out where there's combat.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:48.000
 So if he's just traveling with a field artillery, he'll have his cloths,

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:55.000
 which will be moderately flame-retardant, insect-repellent as well, and 25% Kevlar.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:59.000
 If he's in a tank mission, he's really fire-resistant.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:04.000
 It's a really strong fire-resistant, but that's too expensive for day-to-day use.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:08.000
 And then when he's back at just the camp, he's just wearing normal clothes.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:12.000
 But yeah, he's got three different outfits for not catching on fire.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
 Very clever.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.000
 Fetch the asbestos priest.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:22.000
 And he also, he doesn't carry any weapons, but he does have an assistant with him at all times who has a gun,

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:25.000
 so that's the protection.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:30.000
 And they do, they have all these things that they have, like they have portable confessionals,

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:33.000
 should they need to have a quick confessional out in the field.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:40.000
 They have containers that are turned into chapels, and they have extended shelf-life communion wafers.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:41.000
 It's very cool.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:44.000
 No one likes a stale communion wafer.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:49.000
 So I was trying to find out about more priests, and there was someone called Hugh Barrett Leonard,

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:54.000
 who was a British clergyman who had a title which was "Extraordinary Confessor,"

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.000
 which is a proper title, but he really pushed it.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:04.000
 So once when a woman asked to hear confession outside a church, he just held up a tennis racket between them.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:08.000
 That's amazing.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:14.000
 The telegraph ran his obituary, and it said that although he mostly heard confessions in his room,

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:18.000
 he was prepared to do so behind a hedge.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:19.000
 That's so good.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:23.000
 We have such a tradition of weird clergy in the UK, don't we?

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:26.000
 There was a guy called the Reverend Edward Drax Free,

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:31.000
 and his congregation tried to get him out of the priesthood because he was repeatedly drunk

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:35.000
 and he was stealing lead from the church roof.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:41.000
 And to stop them from getting rid of him, he decided to lock himself in this study with his favourite maid,

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:47.000
 a brace of pistols, and a stack of French pornography.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:51.000
 That's a real slam on the maid, I think.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:55.000
 There was another guy from the 1800s called Reverend Robert Hawker,

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:59.000
 and he was both a priest and a mermaid.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:02.000
 That was the thing he really wanted to be.

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:07.000
 So he made a wig out of seaweed, and then he was naked apart from oil skin around his legs,

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:10.000
 and he rode out to a rock, which was called Bute Harbour,

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:16.000
 and he sat on it and he just would sing, and then go home and, you know, go to church.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:21.000
 Didn't his sort of mermaid rain end, or merman rain end,

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.000
 when he went out and he did this as a prank for the locals,

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:28.000
 and everyone was looking at him through their eyeglasses they had at the time,

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:31.000
 and then he overheard one of the bigger, burlier farmers go,

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:34.000
 "Right, I'm going to go and get my gun, we've got to shoot him down."

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:38.000
 And he ducked underwater and never tried the prank again, I think.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:43.000
 Some stuff on maybe cannons or guns or something like that, that's what the fact's about.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:47.000
 So the cannon kind of came into Europe in the 16th century.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:51.000
 Before that they used trebuchets, which was where they flung stuff along,

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:57.000
 and a lot of people liked them because of their phallicism, for obvious reasons.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:04.000
 So at the siege of Mirandola, the Pope at the time, Pope Julius, was quoted as saying,

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:10.000
 "Now we'll see whose bowls are bigger, mine or Louis's."

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:14.000
 And they also thought, because they were so phallic in shape,

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:18.000
 they thought that if you could make them excited, it would stop them from working.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:21.000
 And so at the siege... honestly...

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
 - What? - Yeah.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:28.000
 At the siege of Chekiang in 1861 to 1862,

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:33.000
 Taiping rebels had prostitutes take off their trousers and moon the forces

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:37.000
 in the hope that it would cause the cannon to misfire or burst.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:42.000
 Honestly, it's history, Anna.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:46.000
 That feels like a flimsy excuse by the Taiping rebels.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:51.000
 Wow. Well, some ships' guns have things called tampions,

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:54.000
 which comes from exactly the same route as tampons.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:56.000
 And these are basically plugs for the guns,

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:59.000
 and it's to stop the guns' insides rusting when they're not being used.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:03.000
 And there used to be an old method of doing it, which was really cool, to stop rust.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:08.000
 They would just put a cannonball inside the barrel and then slosh a load of olive oil inside.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:11.000
 And so then when the ship's bumping up and down,

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:14.000
 the cannonball rolls the olive oil up and down the barrel, and it doesn't rust.

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:17.000
 - Oh, cool. Very clever. - Very clever.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:23.000
 I read about a... it's not a cannon, it's a gun type, but it wasn't shooting bullets.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:27.000
 This is a thing that would shoot into the air a bunch of mines

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:30.000
 that would be attached to parachutes, so mines like you would get in the ground.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:33.000
 The idea is that this was to stop ships from being attacked by planes.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:37.000
 So the planes would come, the parachutes would latch onto the planes,

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:41.000
 tangle up, swing the mines into the plane, and explode the plane.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.000
 So that was the idea. It's an incredible idea.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:46.000
 The problem was is they kept launching these into the sky,

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:49.000
 and the airplanes could see them, and they knew what was coming,

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:52.000
 so they could get out of the way. So it never got them.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:56.000
 And what actually they didn't really count on is there's a lot of wind out there,

00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:00.000
 and very often the wind would blow the mines on the parachutes right back to the boat

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:04.000
 that launched them, and they suffered more British deaths from that than they did.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:06.000
 - Wow. - When was that?

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:09.000
 It was in... I believe it was in the Second World War.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:12.000
 - Really? - But we can edit that out.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:17.000
 The torpedoes. So you could have torpedoes and ships,

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:21.000
 and they've just invented a new torpedo that can fire humans.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.000
 - What? - So this is...

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:26.000
 I believe, even though I haven't seen it, it's in You Only Live Twice.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:30.000
 James Bond gets in a torpedo gun and gets fired through it.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:33.000
 I read on the internet. That may be true or maybe not true.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:36.000
 But apparently there's this new thing where you can get in a little kind of

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:40.000
 torpedo-shaped thing with you and your mate, and it will fire you off,

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:43.000
 and it helps you to get closer to the enemy.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:50.000
 It's over a range of 10... It says 10 nm, which I don't think is nanometers.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:55.000
 - Oh, nautical miles. - Nautical miles.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:29:01.000
 - Hang on, a torpedo is 10 nautical miles? - 10 nautical miles, yeah.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:05.000
 - How do you survive the landing? - Well, you're underwater the whole way.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:07.000
 - Underwater? - It's a torpedo.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:10.000
 But some of the earliest torpedoes were... You got it?

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:15.000
 But some of the earliest torpedoes were underwater ones.

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:17.000
 And they were... Oh, my God.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:21.000
 It's catching.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:26.000
 Some of the earliest torpedoes were rideable torpedoes.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:29.000
 In fact, some of the very first ones had two-man crews

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:32.000
 where you would get on it and motor yourself along,

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:36.000
 and then you would leave the torpedo there next to the enemy ship

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:39.000
 and then hopefully sail around and back.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:42.000
 I've got one last thing, which is on religion and boats,

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.000
 bringing the two things in together.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:48.000
 This is from this year. Two students from Christchurch Academy in Jacksonville,

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:51.000
 which is in Florida, they were swept out to sea.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:54.000
 And it was two of them, and they thought they were going to be lost

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:56.000
 if they were going to die out there.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:59.000
 And they spent their whole time praying to God to be saved.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:02.000
 And they finally were saved by a passing boat.

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:04.000
 And that boat was called Amen.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:07.000
 - How cool is that? - Very nice.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:16.000
 OK, it is time for our final fact of the show, and that is Andy.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:20.000
 My fact is that between 1910 and 1912,

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:25.000
 the Washington Post frequently tried to interview the president's pet cow.

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:32.000
 And was she just very coy, didn't give interviews?

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:36.000
 No, she was very chatty, according to the reporters of the Washington Post.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:39.000
 So this was a specific cow.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:43.000
 She was owned by President William Taft, who was president at the time.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:47.000
 She was actually the last cow ever to graze freely on the White House lawn.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:51.000
 Her name was Pauline Wayne, which is a weird name for a cow.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:57.000
 But they ran over 20 stories about her in this short two-year period.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:02.000
 So one of them, the reporter from the Post, asked her if she was milked without her consent.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:09.000
 And it reported that, "To each query, modest Pauline returned from her soft brown eyes

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:14.000
 at a glance, bespeaking reproach and indignation."

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:17.000
 Which is to say, in bovine, he did not.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
 It's very #MeMoo.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:29.000
 She was very famous. She was a very famous cow.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.000
 You could buy souvenir milk from Pauline Wayne.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:33.000
 She was, and she used to go on tour, didn't she?

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:34.000
 Yeah.

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:36.000
 In fact, she got lost at one point, right?

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:41.000
 She would go on tour around the country, and so her milk could be sold at agricultural fairs and stuff.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:47.000
 And once she was accidentally put on a standard cattle car with the masses of cows

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:51.000
 instead of her usual private luxury cow coach.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:53.000
 And she was taken to the slaughter.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:57.000
 I think she was missing for two days, and there was panic across the land.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.000
 And she was just saved.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:02.000
 This was in 1911, I think. Someone just spotted her in time and said,

